{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 9: Cost-Volume-Profit Analysis\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 9 delves into Cost-Volume-Profit (CVP) analysis, a crucial tool for understanding the relationship between costs, volume, and profit in business decision-making. The chapter covers key concepts such as Contribution, Breakeven Point, and the Contribution to Sales (C/S) Ratio. It also introduces methodologies like the Breakeven Chart and Profit-Volume Chart, which help visualize these relationships. The chapter includes practical examples and quizzes to reinforce learning, such as calculating breakeven sales revenue and drawing breakeven charts. By the end of the chapter, students should be able to apply CVP analysis to real-world scenarios, understand its simplifying assumptions, and use it to make informed business decisions.\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental role of CVP analysis in financial planning and decision-making.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Contribution is a fundamental concept in CVP analysis\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Contribution is the amount remaining from sales revenue after deducting variable costs, which contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit. It is calculated as the difference between sales revenue and variable costs. For Division M, the contribution on external sales is $80 per unit. Contribution is essential for determining the funds available to cover fixed costs and calculate profit [Data: Concepts (439); Relationships (236, 441)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Breakeven Point is critical for understanding business viability\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The breakeven point is the level of activity at which neither a profit nor a loss is made. It is a measure of the lowest activity level at which the activity is viable, where total contribution equals total fixed costs. At this point, total sales equal total costs, ensuring that the company makes neither profit nor loss. The breakeven point is visually represented in a breakeven chart, where the intersection of the total cost and revenue lines indicates the breakeven point [Data: Concepts (438, 442); Relationships (434, 435, 437)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The Contribution to Sales (C/S) Ratio is vital for assessing profitability\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The C/S Ratio is defined as the ratio of the contribution per unit to the selling price per unit. For products C, S, and D, the C/S ratios are 0.55, 0.35, and 0.23 respectively. This ratio is used to determine the profitability of products in both single and multi-product situations. It is a key metric in CVP analysis for assessing how changes in sales volume impact profitability [Data: Concepts (488, 440); Relationships (513, 446)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Breakeven Charts and Profit-Volume Charts are essential visualization tools\",\n            \"explanation\": \"A breakeven chart is a graphical representation that shows the point at which total costs and total revenue are equal. It plots revenue and costs against volume, with the intersection of the total cost and revenue lines indicating the breakeven point. A profit-volume (PV) chart presents the same information but emphasizes profits and losses at different activity levels. These charts help in visualizing the relationship between costs, revenue, and profit at different levels of activity [Data: Concepts (442, 443); Relationships (450, 453)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"CVP analysis includes simplifying assumptions that limit its applicability\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The main limitations of CVP analysis for planning and decision-making stem from the necessary simplifying assumptions. These assumptions include fixed costs remaining constant, the variable cost per unit remaining constant, and the selling price remaining constant. Additionally, CVP analysis assumes that total cost behaves as a strictly linear semi-variable cost, unit selling prices do not change with volume, costs and income are matched, levels of efficiency and productivity do not change, and there is either only a single product or a constant sales mix of more than one product. These assumptions are critical for the analysis but can limit its applicability in more complex, real-world scenarios [Data: Concepts (444); Relationships (455, 456)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Quizzes reinforce the practical application of CVP concepts\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes several quizzes to reinforce the practical application of CVP concepts. For example, one quiz involves calculating the breakeven point in sales revenue for a company that manufactures and sells tables and chairs in a standard mix, given the variable cost per unit, contribution to sales ratio, and annual fixed costs. Another quiz involves drawing a breakeven chart for a product called gamma, with a selling price of $100 per unit, variable cost of $20 per unit, and fixed costs of $1,000,000 per year. These quizzes help students apply theoretical concepts to practical scenarios [Data: Concepts (1408, 446); Relationships (524, 451)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Multi-product profit-volume analysis is crucial for businesses with diverse product lines\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter also covers multi-product profit-volume analysis, which is essential for businesses with diverse product lines. For instance, Hair Co manufactures three types of electrical goods for hair: curlers (C), straightening irons (S), and dryers (D). The analysis involves calculating the weighted average contribution to sales ratio, total break-even revenue, and drawing a multi-product profit-volume chart. This analysis helps in understanding how changes in product mix can affect the overall financial performance of a business [Data: Concepts (2124, 1405); Relationships (1345, 1347)].\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an AI assistant that helps a human analyst to perform general information discovery within a textbook. Information discovery is the process of identifying and assessing relevant information associated with certain entities (e.g., concepts, methodologies, quizzes, examples, cases) within a chapter of a textbook.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive report of a chapter, given a list of concepts, methodologies, formulas and examples that belong to the chapter as well as their relationships and optional associated claims. The report will be used to inform educators and students about the chapter's content and its key components. The content of this report includes an overview of the chapter's key entities, their definitions, interrelations, and noteworthy details.\n\n# Report Structure\n\nThe report should include the following sections:\n\n- TITLE: Chapter title - the title is given in the textbook in the format 'Chapter X: title'\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary that outlines the chapter's structure and the main learning outcomes. Focus on the key concepts as mentioned in the learning outcomes, their relevant examples, formulas, and methodologies, and how these elements are related to each other.\n- IMPACT SEVERITY RATING: a float score between 0-10 that represents the significance of the chapter's content. This score reflects the importance and relevance of the chapter's material in the context of the textbook.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the significance rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the chapter. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format:\n    {{\n        \"title\": <report_title>,\n        \"summary\": <executive_summary>,\n        \"rating\": <impact_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": <rating_explanation>,\n        \"findings\": [\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_1_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_1_explanation>\n            }},\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_2_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_2_explanation>\n            }}\n        ]\n    }}\n\n# Grounding Rules\n\nPoints supported by data should list their data references as follows:\n\n\"This is an example sentence supported by multiple data references [Data: <dataset name> (record ids); <dataset name> (record ids)].\"\n\nDo not list more than 5 record ids in a single reference. Instead, list the top 5 most relevant record ids and add \"+more\" to indicate that there are more.\n\nFor example:\n\"The concept of Expected Value is fundamental to Chapter 8 and is illustrated through multiple examples [Data: Concepts (5, 7, 12); Examples (3, 8, 15, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n439,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Contribution\"\" is the amount remaining from sales revenue after deducting variable costs, which contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit. It is the difference between sales revenue and variable costs. For Division M, the contribution on external sales is $80 per unit. Contribution refers to earnings from sales after deducting variable costs and is computed by deducting variable costs from revenue. The funds available from contribution are used to cover fixed costs, and any excess over fixed costs is considered profit.\",7\n438,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"The breakeven point is the level of activity at which neither a profit nor a loss is made. It is a measure of the lowest activity level at which the activity is viable, where total contribution equals total fixed costs. At this point, total sales equal total costs, ensuring that the company makes neither profit nor loss.\",8\n447,\"\"\"CVP ANALYSIS\"\"\",,8\n442,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN CHART\"\"\",\"A breakeven chart is a graphical representation that shows the point at which total costs and total revenue are equal. It plots revenue and costs against volume, with the intersection of the total cost and revenue lines indicating the breakeven point. This chart helps in visualizing the relationship between costs, revenue, and profit at different levels of activity.\",6\n492,\"\"\"SUMMARY OF CVP ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"The summary of CVP analysis includes the breakeven point, breakeven chart, profit-volume chart, and the limitations due to simplifying assumptions.\"\"\",5\n489,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Breakeven revenue = Fixed cost / C/S ratio\"\"\",3\n488,\"\"\"C/S RATIO\"\"\",\"The \"\"C/S RATIO\"\" is defined as the ratio of the contribution per unit to the selling price per unit. For products C, S, and D, the C/S ratios are 0.55, 0.35, and 0.23 respectively.\",4\n455,\"\"\"TOTAL CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"TOTAL CONTRIBUTION\"\" refers to the total contribution margin, which is calculated as total sales revenue minus total variable costs. This metric, expressed as \"\"Total contribution = Total revenue - Total variable cost,\"\" is essential in financial analysis, particularly for breakeven and target profit calculations.\",4\n440,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION TO SALES RATIO\"\"\",\"The \"\"Contribution to Sales Ratio\"\" is calculated by dividing the contribution per unit by the selling price per unit. This ratio is used to determine the profitability of products in both single and multi-product situations.\",2\n443,\"\"\"PROFIT-VOLUME CHART\"\"\",\"\"\"A profit-volume (PV) chart presents the same information as a breakeven chart but emphasizes profits and losses at different activity levels. It requires information on profit or loss at any level of sales and total fixed costs.\"\"\",2\n444,\"\"\"SIMPLIFYING ASSUMPTIONS OF CVP ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"SIMPLIFYING ASSUMPTIONS OF CVP ANALYSIS\"\"\n\nThe main limitations of CVP (Cost-Volume-Profit) analysis for planning and decision-making stem from the necessary simplifying assumptions. These assumptions include the following: fixed costs remain constant, the variable cost per unit remains constant, and the selling price remains constant. Additionally, CVP analysis assumes that total cost behaves as a strictly linear semi-variable cost, unit selling prices do not change with volume, costs and income are matched, levels of efficiency and productivity do not change, and there is either only a single product or a constant sales mix of more than one product. These assumptions are critical for the analysis but can limit its applicability in more complex, real-world scenarios.\",2\n450,\"\"\"TOTAL REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Total revenue\"\" refers to the total amount of money received from sales of goods or services, calculated by multiplying the sales volume by the sales price per unit. In the context of Best Night Co, total revenue (net of discounts) has increased by 2.4% in 20X7 compared to 20X6. This increase is particularly noteworthy given the tough competitive environment, and any rise in revenues can be seen as a positive outcome. Additionally, as long as the revenue from selling a room exceeds the variable cost of providing it, higher occupancy levels should contribute positively to the hotel's profit.\",3\n445,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF DEPENDENCE ON SALES VOLUME\"\"\",\"\"\"Company A knows the sales price for product X will be around $50, and its variable costs are approximately $30. The contribution per unit is $20. With annual fixed costs of $200,000, Company A needs to sell 10,000 units to break even.\"\"\",1\n1991,\"\"\"GROUP PROFITS\"\"\",\"\"\"Group profits refer to the total profits of the entire organization, considering both internal and external sales.\"\"\",2\n453,\"\"\"OPERATING LEVERAGE\"\"\",\"\"\"Operating leverage is a measure of how sensitive net operating income is to a given percentage change in sales volume. It is influenced by the proportion of fixed costs in a company's cost structure.\"\"\",1\n441,\"\"\"TARGET PROFIT OR REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Target profit or revenue is calculated by determining the sales volume needed to achieve a specific profit level. This involves adding the target profit to the fixed costs and dividing by the contribution per unit.\"\"\",1\n449,\"\"\"SALES PRICE PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Sales price per unit is the amount of money charged to customers for each unit of a product or service. It is a key component in calculating revenue and contribution.\"\"\",1\n495,\"\"\"SELLING PRICE PER UNIT\"\"\",\"The \"\"SELLING PRICE PER UNIT\"\" is the amount a customer pays for a single unit of a product or service. For products C, S, and D, the selling prices per unit are $110, $160, and $120 respectively. The selling price per unit remains constant, as indicated by the straight line of total revenue.\",5\n1405,\"\"\"WEIGHTED AVERAGE CONTRIBUTION TO SALES RATIO\"\"\",\"The \"\"WEIGHTED AVERAGE CONTRIBUTION TO SALES RATIO\"\" is a financial metric used to assess the impact of altering the mix of products produced and sold on the overall profitability. It is calculated by dividing the total contribution by the total revenue, expressed as the weighted average contribution to sales ratio (WA C/S ratio). This ratio helps in understanding how changes in product mix can affect the overall financial performance of a business.\",3\n494,\"\"\"VARIABLE COST PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Variable cost per unit\"\" is the cost that varies with the level of output. It is calculated by summing the per-unit costs of materials, labor, and variable overheads. In this case, it is $21 per unit. Additionally, \"\"variable cost per unit\"\" is represented by the gradient of the total cost line, which is also constant.\",5\n1408,\"\"\"BREAK-EVEN POINT IN SALES REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the break-even point in sales revenue for a company that manufactures and sells tables and chairs in a standard mix, given the variable cost per unit, contribution to sales ratio, and annual fixed costs.\"\"\",2\n1406,\"\"\"BREAK-EVEN SALES REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the break-even sales revenue for a company producing multiple products, given the product mix ratio, contribution to sales ratio for each product, and general fixed costs.\"\"\",2\n446,\"\"\"QUIZ: BREAKEVEN CHART\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves drawing a breakeven chart for a product called gamma, with a selling price of $100 per unit, variable cost of $20 per unit, and fixed costs of $1,000,000 per year. The breakeven level of sales is determined to be 12,500 units.\"\"\",1\n1407,\"\"\"MARGIN OF SAFETY IN UNITS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the margin of safety in units for a company that makes a single product, given the selling price per unit, fixed costs, contribution/sales ratio, and sales revenue.\"\"\",2\n2124,\"\"\"MULTI-PRODUCT PROFIT-VOLUME ANALYSIS FOR HAIR CO'S ELECTRICAL GOODS\"\"\",\"\"\"Hair Co manufactures three types of electrical goods for hair: curlers (C), straightening irons (S), and dryers (D). The budgeted sales prices and volumes for the next year are provided, along with the standard cost card for each product. The case involves calculating the weighted average contribution to sales ratio, total break-even revenue, and drawing a multi-product profit-volume chart.\"\"\",4\n1403,\"\"\"SALES REVENUE LINE\"\"\",\"\"\"The sales revenue line starts at zero and increases steadily as more units are sold.\"\"\",1\n1404,\"\"\"TOTAL COSTS LINE\"\"\",\"\"\"The total costs line starts at zero but rises more quickly at first. After a certain point, it slows down and runs parallel to the sales revenue line, keeping a consistent gap between them.\"\"\",1\n2126,\"\"\"RANKING OF PRODUCTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Ranking of products based on C/S ratio: C is ranked 1, S is ranked 2, and D is ranked 3.\"\"\",1\n2125,\"\"\"HAIR CO'S ELECTRICAL GOODS\"\"\",\"\"\"Hair Co manufactures three types of electrical goods for hair: curlers (C), straightening irons (S), and dryers (D). The budgeted sales prices and volumes for the next year are provided, along with the standard cost card for each product.\"\"\",1\n1907,\"\"\"OPERATING PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Despite the increase in revenue, operating profits have fallen by $0.3m (1.3%) between 20X7 and 20X6, due to a sizeable increase in operating costs.\"\"\",2\n466,\"\"\"TOTAL VARIABLE COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Total variable cost is the total of all variable costs associated with production or sales.\"\"\",1\n1912,\"\"\"FINANCIAL ANALYSIS AND BALANCED SCORECARD EVALUATION FOR EASYAIR CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Easyair Co was founded seven years ago, and is one of a growing number of low-cost airlines in the country of Shania. Summarised financial information for the most recent financial year is provided below: Operating profit: $700m, Interest payable: $100m, Profit before tax: $600m, Tax: $200m, Profit after tax: $400m, Non-current liabilities: $300m, Share capital: $100m, Retained earnings: $2,000m.\"\"\",1\n1990,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Incremental cost is the additional cost incurred when producing one more unit. For Division S, the incremental cost of buying from outside the group is $60 per unit.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n445,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET FOR THE NEXT FOUR QUARTERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Contribution is a key component in the rolling budget for the next four quarters.\"\"\",21\n236,\"\"\"VARIABLE COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Variable costs are deducted from revenue to calculate Contribution, which is used to cover fixed costs and generate profit.\"\"\",16\n434,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Breakeven point is determined when total Contribution equals total fixed costs.\"\"\",15\n294,\"\"\"FIXED COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed costs are a critical component in determining the Breakeven point as they must be covered by the total contribution.\"\"\",15\n441,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"CVP ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"CVP analysis uses Contribution to determine the funds available to cover fixed costs and calculate profit.\"\"\",15\n449,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN CHART\"\"\",\"\"\"CVP ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"CVP analysis uses Breakeven charts to visualize the relationship between costs, revenue, and profit at different levels of activity.\"\"\",14\n435,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"BREAKEVEN CHART\"\"\",\"\"\"Breakeven chart visually represents the Breakeven point where total cost and revenue lines intersect.\"\"\",14\n438,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT FORMULA\"\"\",\"\"\"The breakeven point is calculated using the breakeven point formula.\"\"\",14\n440,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"SUMMARY OF CVP ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Breakeven point is included in the Summary of CVP Analysis.\"\"\",13\n437,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"MARGIN OF SAFETY\"\"\",\"\"\"Margin of safety measures the risk of falling below the Breakeven point by comparing actual or projected sales to the Breakeven sales volume.\"\"\",12\n439,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"BREAKEVEN REVENUE\"\"\",\"\"\"Breakeven point is related to breakeven revenue as both are used to determine the level of sales needed to cover costs.\"\"\",11\n513,\"\"\"C/S RATIO\"\"\",\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"C/S ratio is calculated based on the contribution per unit divided by the sellin